</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Developing RxNorm Extension: A Step Toward Global Drug Data Harmonization in Observational Drug Research</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ostropolets%20A"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Anna Ostropolets</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Anna Ostropolets</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Columbia University, New York NY, United States</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Johnson &amp; Johnson, Titusville NJ, United States</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ostropolets%20A"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Anna Ostropolets</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Zhuk%20A"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Aleh Zhuk</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Aleh Zhuk</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>3</sup>Odysseus, an EPAM Company, Cambridge MA, United States</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Zhuk%20A"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Aleh Zhuk</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>3</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Korchmar%20E"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Eduard Korchmar</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3><span class="name western">Eduard Korchmar</span></h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>3</sup>Odysseus, an EPAM Company, Cambridge MA, United States</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Korchmar%20E"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Eduard Korchmar</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>3</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ryan%20P"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id4"><span class="name western">Patrick Ryan</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id4">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Patrick Ryan</span>, <span class="degrees">PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Columbia University, New York NY, United States</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Johnson &amp; Johnson, Titusville NJ, United States</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ryan%20P"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Patrick Ryan</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Reich%20C"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id5"><span class="name western">Christian Reich</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id5">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Christian Reich</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>4</sup>Northeastern University, Portland ME, United States</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Reich%20C"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Christian Reich</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>4</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="af1-9116">
<sup>1</sup>Columbia University, New York NY, United States</div>
<div id="af2-9116">
<sup>2</sup>Johnson &amp; Johnson, Titusville NJ, United States</div>
<div id="af3-9116">
<sup>3</sup>Odysseus, an EPAM Company, Cambridge MA, United States</div>
<div id="af4-9116">
<sup>4</sup>Northeastern University, Portland ME, United States</div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Collection date 2025.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div>©2025 AMIA - All rights reserved.</div>
<p>This is an Open Access article: verbatim copying and redistribution of this article are permitted in all media for any purpose</p>
<div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC12919553  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/41726498/" class="usa-link">41726498</a>
</div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p>This paper presents RxNorm Extension (RxE), a standardized drug vocabulary system designed to harmonize drug data across international databases. RxE integrates drugs from multiple national drug repositories, enhancing global drug safety and effectiveness research by standardizing drug representations in disparate drug vocabularies to a structure following RxNorm, a reference standard in the US. We developed an attribute-based mapping approach that improves consistency and reduce manual data processing. Based on 12 vocabularies included, we observe similar dose form and ingredient usage patterns but many more brand names available worldwide. The quality of RxE depends on the thorough examination of the source vocabulary, where challenges include discrepancies in brand names, poorly structured dosage forms, and faulty dosages. Despite the challenges, RxE has been used in numerous clinical and methodological studies. Future directions focus on expanding coverage, improving mapping automation, and fostering international collaboration to optimize global drug safety and effectiveness efforts.</p></section><section id="sec1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p>Real-world data (RWD) plays a crucial role in pharmacovigilance by facilitating comprehensive drug monitoring. When a new drug enters the market or when an adverse event of interest is rare, traditional drug surveillance often struggles due to small sample sizes. Real-world evidence (RWE) derived from data source networks can address this limitation by providing access to diverse and extensive patient populations. However, conducting studies across multiple data sources presents a significant challenge due to inconsistencies in drug coding. These discrepancies must be reconciled to ensure the accuracy and reliability of cross-database analyses.</p>
<p>To support global observational research, there is a critical need for a standardized drug vocabulary system that harmonizes drug representations across different national databases. In the United States, the National Library of Medicine provides RxNorm, a comprehensive drug vocabulary system that is freely available (<a href="#r1-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r1-9116">1</a>). RxNorm integrates various drug attributes into a hierarchical structure, allowing researchers to retrieve patient records efficiently based on specific attributes. For instance, all inhalant prednisone preparations—regardless of their strength, supplier, precise dosage form, or packaging—can be systematically identified and retrieved within the RxNorm framework.</p>
<p>Despite its advantages, RxNorm is limited to drugs marketed in the United States, meaning that medications available exclusively in other countries are not included. To address this gap, we developed a heuristic approach to construct RxNorm Extension, a novel drug repository that integrates data from multiple national drug databases.</p>
<p>The necessity for such an extension becomes apparent when studying adverse events associated with specific drug classes, such as histamine H2 receptor antagonists like cimetidine, on a global scale. Each country maintains its own drug coding system, requiring researchers to identify cimetidine-related entries in BDPM (France), AMIS (Germany), DPD (Canada), NDC and RxNorm (United States), dm+d (United Kingdom), and many other national repositories. The variation in naming conventions, coding structures, and languages makes comprehensive data retrieval a labor-intensive, time-consuming, and error-prone process. Although proprietary platforms such as the Multinational Integrated Data Analysis System (MIDAS) offer a commercial solution for global drug studies—such as those involving gabapentinoids (<a href="#r2-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r2-9116">2</a>)—there is currently no open-source alternative that enables similar multinational analyses.</p>
<p>In response to this challenge, we developed RxNorm Extension, a unified drug vocabulary system designed to incorporate medications from global markets into a standardized framework. This paper details the methodology used to create RxNorm Extension, the obstacles encountered during its development, and the implications of this new system for pharmacovigilance and global drug safety research.</p></section><section id="sec2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Methods</h2>
<section id="sec2_1"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Principles of RxNorm Extension</h3>
<p>RxNorm Extension (RxE) relies on the universal system of describing drugs that follows and expands upon RxNorm structure (<a href="#f1-9116" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>).</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f1-9116"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 1.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12919553_AMIASYMPROC-2025-9116-f1.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/5139/12919553/3eed3b87bc63/AMIASYMPROC-2025-9116-f1.jpg" loading="lazy" height="365" width="738" alt="Figure 1."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f1-9116/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Representation of drugs according to combination of their attributes in RxNorm Extension</p></figcaption></figure><p>It follows two key principles to support global research. First, incorporating local drugs into RxE does not require direct mapping to existing RxNorm concepts. Instead, local drug attributes—such as ingredients, dose forms, and brand names—are matched systematically to ensure consistency and reliability. Second, like RxNorm, RxE maintains a comprehensive drug hierarchy, allowing users to select an appropriate level of detail (such as all oral cimetidine products by selecting Clinical Drug Form and all descendants), improving usability and reducing errors.</p>
<p>The process of integrating a vocabulary into RxE involves several steps:
</p>
<ul class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p>Mapping drug codes to existing concepts in RxNorm or RxNorm extension based on attribute equivalence.</p></li>
<li><p>Creating new RxNorm Extension concepts if no valid equivalent is available. This may include active Ingredients not approved for marketing in the US (e.g., pipradrol), a rare new drug form such as medicated nail polishes and (most common) new strength and brand names (ImmuCyst, Kanuma, Loceryl).</p></li>
<li><p>Adjusting RxE when RxNorm updates overwrite existing RxE concepts (if a drug is approved by the FDA after it already had market approval elsewhere).</p></li>
</ul></section><section id="sec2_2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Input files</h3>
<p>In the first step of local vocabulary preparation, input tables have to be prepared from the source vocabulary-specific information. Input tables are standardized, allowing systematic processing regardless of the source vocabulary structure.</p>
<p>drug_concept_stage contains the information about source drug products and source drug attributes: ingredients or active substance(s) in pharmacological preparation, brand names or marketed names, dose forms or form in which drug is administered to patient, units, and suppliers or manufacturers. A simplified version for a drug coming from a Japanese drug vocabulary (JMDC) - Cimetidine 40% 1g Cimetiparl – is presented in <a href="#t2-9116" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="t2-9116"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 2.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p>Sample of drug_concept_stage table</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">concept_name</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">vocabulary_id</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">concept_class_id</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">concept_code</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Cimetidine 40% 1g Cimetiparl</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Drug Product</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">100000000081</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Cimetiparl</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Brand Name</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC5235</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Fine Granule</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Dose Form</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC5969</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">cimetidine</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Ingredient</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC48</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">%</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Unit</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">g</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">JMDC</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Unit</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">g</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/t2-9116/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p>If the source does not provide separate attributes, the drug strings need to be parsed. Every drug must have at least one ingredient, other attributes are optional.</p>
<p>Second table, internal_relationship_stage, links from a drug product to a respective ‘Ingredient’, ‘Brand Name’, ‘Supplier’ and ‘Dose Form’ if available (<a href="#t3-9116" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>).</p>
