<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/t5-9116/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p>The process of attribute matching can be ambiguous. For instance, dose forms may have different names or levels of granularity across drug systems. The strength of a drug can be based on the pure ingredient or on a salt, ether, ester, or chelate. Additionally, ingredients may be expressed in different units (e.g., mg or mL), and determining the equivalence of supplier organizations across countries can be complex.</p>
<p>As a result, attribute mappings are not always one-to-one. Instead, they may be one-to-many—for example, a single incoming dose form might correspond to multiple RxNorm/RxNorm Extension dose forms. These mappings are often ranked by an order of precedence score, which indicates confidence in the match. Precedence score is set by the team that integrates the vocabulary and oftentimes requires knowledge about drug market or pharmaceutical knowledge. For example, <a href="#t5-9116" class="usa-link">Table 5</a> shows that the team determined that Oral Granules is the best match for Fine Granules in source vocabulary, while Oral Flakes can also be a potential match but with lower precedence. Later, the system integrates these mappings based on their precedence rankings.</p></section><section id="sec2_3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Assembly process</h3>
<p>In the second step of the process, input files are utilized to map incoming drugs based on their attributes rather than relying on lexical methods. This step is fully automated and available as open-source (<a href="#r3-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r3-9116">3</a>). It effectively resolves ambiguity in attribute mapping, as previously described, while also factoring in the confidence level associated with a target concept—often referred to as the “social life of a concept.”</p>
<p>For instance, a drug that is widely available across multiple markets in the same combination of active ingredient, dosage form, and strength will be prioritized in fuzzy mapping scenarios over a drug with limited presence in various drug markets. Differences in lower hierarchy attributes, such as branding, suppliers, and packaging, are considered secondary when determining the best match.</p>
<p>To further enhance accuracy, the script manages input attribute ambiguity by implementing a 10% corridor for dosage matching. It systematically selects the set of attributes that most closely align with existing drugs in the predefined input groups. When mapping, it prioritizes drugs that are prevalent across markets, ensuring consistency and reducing potential mismatches.</p></section><section id="sec2_4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Quality assurance and control</h3>
<p>The overall quality of the output depends significantly on the precision of attribute mappings and the integrity of the existing RxNorm and RxNorm Extension concepts and hierarchies. If these reference systems degrade in quality, even the most accurate input data cannot prevent inconsistencies or errors.</p>
<p>To maintain integrity, the system performs rigorous checks on the input data, including:
</p>
<ul class="list" style="list-style-type:disc">
<li><p>Flagging dosages without specified units, as well as doses exceeding 1 mg/mg or 1000 mg/mL.</p></li>
<li><p>Identifying ingredients listed without corresponding dosage information or solid formulations (e.g., tablets, capsules) erroneously assigned liquid dosages.</p></li>
<li><p>Detecting instances where ingredients are mistakenly used as brand names (e.g., Clopidogrel/Aspirin or Ibuprofen and Codeine).</p></li>
<li><p>Identifying potential unmapped attributes that could lead to duplication or inconsistencies.</p></li>
</ul>
<p>If errors or logical discrepancies are detected within the input tables, the execution process is halted to prevent inaccuracies from propagating.</p>
<p>Whenever feasible, post-release quality assurance is conducted by comparing patient counts retrieved through source coding with those obtained via the RxNorm-RxE reference standard. This additional verification step helps ensure the robustness and reliability of the mappings.</p></section><section id="sec2_5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Output</h3>
<p>The semi-automated process establishes links between source drugs and their corresponding counterparts in standard vocabularies. If an exact match is unavailable, new RxE terms are generated to accommodate the data (<a href="#f2-9116" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a>). Additionally, the assembly script constructs a hierarchical framework, integrating newly created terms into the existing structure. For example, in the case of cimetidine, a newly introduced RxE term was linked to the RxNorm ingredient, ensuring appropriate placement within the reference hierarchy.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f2-9116"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 2.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12919553_AMIASYMPROC-2025-9116-f2.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/5139/12919553/4d65fd33d5fe/AMIASYMPROC-2025-9116-f2.jpg" loading="lazy" height="426" width="752" alt="Figure 2."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f2-9116/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Sample structure of RxNorm-RxNorm Extension hierarchy created based on the source drug containing cimetidine.</p></figcaption></figure><p>The assembly algorithm can also operate in a “mapping-only” mode, which aligns source drugs with their closest equivalents in the reference corpus without generating new concepts. This functionality is particularly beneficial when dealing with lower-quality source vocabularies—such as those containing abbreviated drug descriptions—while ensuring compatibility with a pre-existing, high-quality vocabulary that has already been integrated for a specific country or drug market.</p></section></section><section id="sec3"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Results</h2>
<p>RxE usability has been showcased through its use in numerous methodological and clinical studies around the world (<a href="#r4-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r4-9116">4</a>–<a href="#r24-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r24-9116">24</a>). Notably, it supports the activities of the European Health Data and Evidence Network and the Data Analysis and Real World Interrogation Network inititative study activities (<a href="#r25-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r25-9116">25</a>,<a href="#r26-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r26-9116">26</a>). Several works showcase use of RxE in data harmonization to OMOP CDM (<a href="#r27-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r27-9116">27</a>–<a href="#r31-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r31-9116">31</a>).</p>
<p>As of March 2025, RxE incorporates information from 12 source vocabularies across ten countries: AMIS (Germany), AMT (Australia), BDPM (France), dm+d (UK), DPD (Canada), EDI (Korea), Gemscript (UK), GGR (Belgium), GRR (Brazil), JMDC (Japan), KDC (Korea) and Z-index (Netherlands) and contains the information about drugs not available within RxNorm. RxE is integrated with RxNorm into a joint reference standard within OHDSI as is arranged into a single hierarchy. We integrated Anatomic Therapeutic Classification (ATC) into this system as a classification vocabulary and enables users to group drugs represented through RxE or RxNorm codes according to therapeutic group and provides better coverage compared to other initiatives (<a href="#r4-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r4-9116">4</a>,<a href="#r32-9116" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="r32-9116">32</a>).</p>
<p><a href="#f3-9116" class="usa-link">Figure 3</a> shows the distribution of main classes within RxE in comparison with RxNorm. Orange boxes represent the drug codes for which RxE relies on RxNorm terms instead of creating new terms (overlap). For example, RxE reuses 5,537 ingredients from RxNorm and have 2,116 active ingredients not available in RxNorm. Additionally, RxE has a number of new and experimental susbtances provided by the source vocabularies and not yet available in marketed formulations such as ablukast, sibofimloc or varlilumab.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="f3-9116"><h3 class="obj_head">Figure 3.</h3>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><a class="tileshop" target="_blank" href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/core/lw/2.0/html/tileshop_pmc/tileshop_pmc_inline.html?title=Click%20on%20image%20to%20zoom&amp;p=PMC3&amp;id=12919553_AMIASYMPROC-2025-9116-f3.jpg"><img class="graphic zoom-in" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/5139/12919553/ac80f997d003/AMIASYMPROC-2025-9116-f3.jpg" loading="lazy" height="420" width="721" alt="Figure 3."></a></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/f3-9116/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Unique and overlapping drug terms in RxNorm and RxE stratified by selected drug classes. More drug classes are available within these vocabularies.</p></figcaption></figure><p><a href="#f3-9116" class="usa-link">Figure 3</a> illustrates that, as expected, most of the content of RxE is international drugs that share the ingredients with the US drugs but are not available in the US in the same dosage (Clinical Drugs) or brand and/or dosage (Branded Drugs). Overall, there are twice as many Clinical Drugs as Branded Drugs in RxNorm, while in RxNorm Extension there are two times more Branded Drugs than Clinical Drugs, which can be explained by a high overlap of drugs under different names but with same strength and form across international markets.</p>
<p>Ingredient combinations stay relatively stable worldwide. RxNorm has 40.8% Clinical Drugs containing single active ingredient and 51.2% Clinical Drugs contain several ingredients, while worldwide marked additionally contribute drugs that are 70.2% single-ingredient and 29.8% several-ingredients. Overall, single-ingredient drugs in worldwide markets exceed multi-ingredient set more than twice, and this number is likely going to increase further the addition of national drug repositories.</p>
<p>In both US and international markets, mono-ingredient drugs are more often branded than multi-ingredient drugs: 77.2% and 81.4% of RxNorm and RxE Branded Drugs respectively have one ingredient.</p>
<p>International markets also exhibit different dose form use patterns. For example, Clinical Drugs available as oral solution account for only 14% of oral Clinical Drugs in RxNorm but for 35.6% of oral Clinical Drugs in RxE making it the most common oral drug form. On the other hand, we observed consistency in distribution of different forms of oral tablet formulations in the US and internationally: among delayed release, extended release and plain oral tablets the latter accounted for 84% and 86% of Clinical Drugs in RxNorm and RxE respectively.</p></section><section id="sec4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Discussion</h2>
<p>The integration of RxNorm and RxNorm Extension provides a robust framework for standardizing drug vocabularies across various international markets. This system facilitates the accurate representation of patient drug exposure data, enhancing the consistency and reliability of pharmacological studies. Our semi-automated process streamlines the transformation of diverse drug products into this standardized structure, significantly reducing the effort compared to traditional drug-to-drug mapping approaches. By deconstructing each drug into fundamental attributes—such as ingredient, brand, dosage form, strength, and manufacturer—and mapping these to corresponding RxNorm or RxE attributes, we achieve efficient standardization.</p>
<p>Despite these advancements, the RxE transformation process necessitates proficiency in both SQL and pharmaceutical product knowledge, potentially limiting its accessibility to all researchers. Consequently, some research groups have developed localized mappings instead of utilizing the standardized RxE system. This practice introduces challenges for collaborative studies, especially when identical source vocabularies are mapped differently across research sites. Additionally, discrepancies can occur when RxNorm lacks specific formulations available in other markets, hindering accurate mapping at the appropriate level. Many alternative vocabularies represent drug products in an unstructured manner without clearly defined attributes, further complicating standardization efforts. It is, therefore, important for us as maintainers to introduce new informatics solutions to lower the barriers for integrating and maintaining local vocabularies into RxE. While there are user interfaces to explore RxE (athena.ohdsi.org) and to use it and its hierarchy to create concept sets (such as atlas-demo.ohdsi.org), there are no user-friendly solutions for source drug parsing or mapping.</p>
<p>Attention to attribute processing and mapping is crucial, as errors introduced into RxE can propagate with each maintenance update, compromising data consistency. Currently, these issues are addressed manually by the development team; however, there is a pressing need to establish automated quality control procedures to enhance efficiency and accuracy.</p>
<p>A significant source of ambiguity in RxE is the handling of brand names. Variations in brand names across global markets and inconsistencies in source data quality can lead to duplicate entries if harmonization is not carefully managed. For example, determining whether the “Nicabate” brand encompasses related products such as “Nicabate Clear,” “Nicabate CQ,” “Nicabate Mini,” and others, or whether these should be treated as distinct brands, is challenging. A more granular approach increases the number of unique drug entries that might otherwise have been consolidated. Additionally, there is no standardized convention for handling brand names that include dosage distinctions, such as “Albunate,” “Albunate-5,” “Albunate-20,” and “Albunate-25.” Brand names also vary across countries, making it impossible to represent them with a single concept. For instance, OMOP918724 Desogestrel / Ethinyl Estradiol Oral Tablet [Desmin] from a German vocabulary and OMOP4670184 Desmopressin Oral Tablet [Desmin] from a Korean vocabulary share the same brand name despite being entirely different drugs.</p>
<p>Another challenge arises from the lack of international conventions distinguishing drugs from medical devices. While RxNorm generally provides guidance on this classification, its definitions evolve over time. Some products appearing in drug vocabularies should not be categorized as drugs, such as liquid soaps, white ointments, valine-free milk, and phenylalanine-free milk. Other items, including electrolyte solutions and blood products, introduce complexity and may require additional classification standards to prevent errors in RxE.</p>
<p>The diversity of drug formulations also presents challenges in standardization. If a source vocabulary provides only a generic dose form (e.g., “oral pill”), it must be mapped to all potential variants, such as Oral Tablet, Extended Release, Delayed Release, Effervescent, and Disintegrating. However, if a specific dosage form exists but is not captured in the source vocabulary, misclassification may occur, leading to inconsistencies in the dataset.</p>
<p>Additionally, the RxNorm lifecycle must be carefully managed within the RxE system. When RxNorm deprecates a parent concept linked to an RxE concept without providing a direct replacement—often due to concept splits—the RxE concept loses its hierarchical placement. If not properly addressed, this can result in lost ingredient relationships or the unintended duplication of drug records. For instance, “Interferon Alfa-2b Intramuscular Solution [Intron A]” was added to RxE despite RxNorm already including “Interferon Alfa-2b Injectable Solution [Intron A],” simply because the intramuscular form was not explicitly categorized as injectable.</p>
<p>Moreover, when RxNorm replaces an existing RxE attribute, incorrect handling of attribute transitions can lead to redundancy. If relations to deprecated concepts remain active, RxE concepts may retain multiple links to the same class attribute—one outdated and one current. These inconsistencies may evade standard quality control checks, as new RxNorm concepts may introduce variations in precise ingredient names, component ordering, base ingredients for dosages, or rounding conventions (e.g., 366 mg vs. 367 mg).</p>
<p>Addressing these challenges requires a concerted effort to improve automation, establish international conventions, and refine quality control mechanisms within the RxE framework. Future directions include developing automated procedures for attribute processing and mapping, harmonizing brand name conventions across markets, clarifying the distinction between drugs and medical devices, standardizing the representation of diverse dosage forms, and effectively managing the RxNorm lifecycle to maintain hierarchical integrity. Additionally, we plan to expand the coverage by integrating other known drug vocabularies: AEMPS (Spain), AmiCE (Germany), Laegemiddeloplysninger, (Denmark), CHNM (Portugal), UCD (France), JKL (Serbia), BNF (UK), VNR (Finland), APB (Turkey) and others. By tackling these issues, we aim to enhance drug standardization for global pharmacovigilance and research, ultimately improving patient safety and the efficacy of healthcare interventions.</p></section><section id="sec5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h2>
<p>We developed RxNorm Extension as a response to the global need for drug data standardization for observational research. By integrating drugs from various national databases, RxE facilitates large-scale drug safety analyses while maintaining consistency across datasets. Its attribute-based mapping approach allows for flexibility in incorporating non-U.S. drugs, and automation reduces manual effort in data harmonization. However, challenges remain, including brand name variability, dosage form inconsistencies, and classification ambiguities. Future efforts should focus on expanding coverage, refining computational mapping, and fostering international collaboration to optimize RxE’s impact on global drug safety research.</p></section><section id="sec11"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Figures &amp; Tables</h2></section><section id="ref-list1" class="ref-list"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">References</h2>
<section id="ref-list1_sec2"><ul class="ref-list font-sm" style="list-style-type:none">
<li id="r1-9116">
<span class="label">1.</span><cite>Bodenreider O, Cornet R, Vreeman D. Recent Developments in Clinical Terminologies — SNOMED CT, LOINC, and RxNorm. Yearbook of Medical Informatics. 2018 Aug;27(01):129–39. doi: 10.1055/s-0038-1667077.</cite> [<a href="https://doi.org/10.1055/s-0038-1667077" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">DOI</a>] [<a href="/articles/PMC6115234/" class="usa-link">PMC free article</a>] [<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30157516/" class="usa-link">PubMed</a>] [<a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?journal=Yearbook%20of%20Medical%20Informatics&amp;title=Recent%20Developments%20in%20Clinical%20Terminologies%20%E2%80%94%20SNOMED%20CT,%20LOINC,%20and%20RxNorm&amp;author=O%20Bodenreider&amp;author=R%20Cornet&amp;author=D%20Vreeman&amp;volume=27&amp;issue=01&amp;publication_year=2018%20Aug&amp;pages=129-39&amp;pmid=30157516&amp;doi=10.1055/s-0038-1667077&amp;" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google Scholar</a>]</li>
